caption:
Nobody wants to live in the past, we just want the clothes.
Like this man's jacket and stunning embroidered waistcoat, made in France c. 1790.
The bottom of the waistcoat is embroidered with Roman ruins.
Kyoto Costume Institute, üì∑ Toru Kogure. Items AC5146 85-28-2AC, AC5667 87-35-1
alt_text: The Kyoto Costume Institute has the jacket, waistcoat, and trousers. This photo shows the jacket and waistcoat and just an inch or two of the green trousers' waistband. The jacket is satin, with blue and green vertical stripes, a fold back standing collar, and buttons decorated with angular geometric patterns. And that waistcoat!  Vivid blue, embroidered with stems and flowers running up the center and continuing on the stand-up collar, and embroidered with ruined Roman arches and outbuildings along the bottom edge. Under the waistcoat at the neck and cuffs we see lovely white frills from the shirt underneath.

caption: The NeXTlevel was NeXT Software's first handheld device, eagerly awaited but canned just two weeks from release when Apple purchased NeXT and chose not to pursue gaming. All 250,000 release devices were pulled from channels and unceremoniously rolled into landfill out northwest of Dubbo.
alt_text: A picture of a black NeXTlevel handheld gaming device, by NeXT. It opens vertically to show two landscape screens, a dpad, and four buttons in NeXT colours. On the bottom screen is the NeXT desktop with the Info window for Chess showing. On the top screen is Chess in its 3D NeXT style glory. Either side of the top screen are the speaker grilles. It sits on a blue fabric background, lit from the side.

caption: A triangular console with triangular cartridges, the Telstar Arcade was the last entry in the Coleco Telstar line, and it certainly left an impression.
alt_text: A brown triangular prism.  The top side is used to for the triangular top-loading cartridges (this cartridge has Road Race, Tennis, and Quick Draw).  The facing side is the pinball interface, with two paddles, a rotary switch, 'Slam Left', 'Slam Right', a skill selector, a power switch, and a reset button.  The far side is a racing interface, with steering wheel and gear selector.  The right side is shooting game interface, with a realistic looking sidearm and three buttons in holes.  The interface panels alternate woodgrain and faux metal.

caption: One of the most obscure computers I have ever looked up, the Gradiente Expert was a MSX computer for the Brasilian market; a reissue of the National CF-3000 for the Japanese market, styled like a contemporary audio box, cheaper than a C64 but hampered by an incomplete MSX implementation.
alt_text: A three-piece computer unit.  Up top, the white monitor reads:  "MSX BASIC vers√£o 1.1 Br 'G r a d i e n t e' 28014 bytes livres OK" up top, then "color auto goto list run" down below.  The computer itself is a grey pizzabox, with black angular highlighting joining the two cartidge slots and the power light.  Image bottom, the Expert's keyboard; a full keyboard, it includes multimedia buttons, a blue directional keypad, and the same angular black highlighting as is on the face of the computer proper.  A small recess in the computer allows the keyboard to be locked in place, although this seems only to be to hold the keyboard in position, not to store the keyboard.

caption: One of the most obscure computers I have ever looked up, the Gradiente Expert was a MSX computer for the Brasilian market; a reissue of the National CF-3000 for the Japanese market, styled like a contemporary audio box, cheaper than a C64 but hampered by an incomplete MSX implementation.
alt_text: A three-piece computer unit.  Up top, the white monitor reads:  "MSX BASIC vers√£o 1.1 Br 'G r a d i e n t e' 28014 bytes livres OK" up top, then "color auto goto list run" down below.  The computer itself is a grey pizzabox, with black angular highlighting joining the two cartidge slots and the power light.  Image bottom, the Expert's keyboard; a full keyboard, it includes multimedia buttons, a blue directional keypad, and the same angular black highlighting as is on the face of the computer proper.  A small recess in the computer allows the keyboard to be locked in place, although this seems only to be to hold the keyboard in position, not to store the keyboard.

alt_text:
A cover for the fictional magazine Tomboy BiMonthly done for Pride Month, headed by two little pride flags for transgender and non-binary people. It features my characters Chandelle on the left and Modeste on the right. Chandelle is sitting down and wearing a navy suit with a dull gold tie and matching spats, with a checkered vest combining both colors. Her hair is cropped short in her usual haircut and she has bigass eyebrows because she's gender like that. She is smiling up at Modeste, who is leaning on a bar counter. She is wearing her full dress 5th Hussard uniform, which is made up of a sky blue dolman and kepi with gold buttons and white braiding, a black trimmed navy pelisse also with white braiding, red and navy pants and leather riding boots and gaiters. She has a Mle1882 revolver holster strapped across her chest and she is holding one glove in her hand, with the other naked one resting on the butt of her saber which I've got to say is pretty hot. Don't hate.
The overall color palette is warm with many shades of gold. The bottom of the picture is filled with a frame quote from a real book, the 'Illustrated Book of Manners: a Manual of Good Behavior and Polite Accomplishments' published in 1866, which explicitly says it's fine for women to have male gender expression actually.

caption:
"The Cultivation of Purpose"

Two 9" x 12" pages done on watercolor paper with a mix of sumi ink, watercolors, and airbrushed acrylics. 

I wrote these pages a few years ago, and am happy to finally share them with you.
alt_text: Watercolor comic page: Opening on a close up shot of a red rose in a dimly lit flag stone room. A pair of shears comes up and prunes the blossom from the plant, revealing a young woman with red hair and a dim blue dress. She asks, "What are you doing" to the gardener. Said gardener is a woman in a fine black dress with pearl buttons. Her fingernails are long and sharp like the thorns of the rose bush she is attending. She responds with a voice similar to that of her aged shears, "In order to properly cultivate a plant such as this, one must see to the removal of diseased material... Lest the rot spreads". She punctuates this with the sharp removal of another bud. "But," the young woman responds looking to a rose at the gardeners feet, "You're only removing the blossoms. Why grow roses only to prune their beauty?"

The bodice is trimmed with chenille, fastens with metal buttons and is lined with silk, cotton and whalebone strips. High round neck, wide pagoda sleeves, and fastens down the centre front. It is waist length and has a peak front and back. The sleeves are trimmed with an applied band of gathered silk ribbon, and matching chenille rosettes with silk tassels stitched on either side of the centre front from shoulders to waist. The cast metal stud buttons are on either side of a silvered centre. A narrow double rouleau trims the neck and waist. Silk pads are stitched at the bosom. The sleeves are lined with white silk.

The skirt fastens at the centre back and is double flat pleated. It is lined with organdie and has a matching brush braid. The waist band is tucked to shape and fastens with two brass hooks and eyes. A small watch pocket is stitched into it.

alt_text:
Hien Pham is a bearded, bald, fat Asian man wearing glasses and who has spots and scars on his butt. He draws in a cartoon-y but realistically rendered style with the full spectrum of colors.

A little nervously, Hien undoes the buttons of his red shirt and takes a glance over his shoulder. As he pulls down his white boxers we see that he is undressing in the back of a yoga studio, by the shelves for patrons belongings. In the foreground, he is framed by the arms and upper legs of two seated, hairy figures. One last time for luck, Hien quickly ruffles his fingers through his short beard hairs, gives them a gentle tug and then exhales calmly. 

"Welcome, everyone, to naked yoga." Greets a voice off panel to the assembled variety of men sitting on their yoga mats on the floor. They have a diverse range of skin tones, builds, and body hair. Hien sits in the center of the group with his legs crossed and his hands resting over his ankles. He looks excited and nervous at the same time.

Big Star wears a fluffy white hat with Christmas Roses pinned to one side of it, a powder blue shawl with gold trim, and a golden gauntlet on his right hand, in which he wields a gold sword with a red gem in the hilt. He has a mildly surprised expression. Under his powder blue coat is a green shirt with a golden star-shaped plate over his chest, and two fluffy white buttons. Killia is wearing a brown reindeer-themed hoodie with large antlers extending from it, a cream ruffle around his neck, and speckled brown shoulders. Christo is wearing his fake demon horns, dark blue and pink hair decorations, and dark pink goggles which he is lifting from his eyes as he glances toward the viewer. His sleeve is blue with a cream trim, his glove is dark purple, and the cloak he wears is the same shade, with a similar trim. There's a long streak of grey in his green hair. He's holding a large, brown bag, and is posed like he's running. Fuji's dark hair is worn in a long, low ponytail, tied by snowball-shaped hair ties. Hanging from his large horns are snowy decorations, and around his neck is a blue cross-tie with a pair of snowball fasteners. He is bare-chested aside from that. caption: Second, the number of buttons‚Äîone, two, or three‚Äîhas social meaning. A one button configuration is typically considered more formal than it's two- or three-button counterparts, so you typically see it on evening wear and formalwear.
alt_text: Tom Brady in a midnight navy velvet dinner jacket, white shirt, and black formal trousers. The jacket has a shawl collar and one-button closure.

caption: Regardless of the origins, there are two important things to understand. First, tailored jackets are often cut in such a way that the bottom button can't be fastened without dragging the coat's front edge. See how this bottom button doesn't even align with the buttonhole.
alt_text: Italian actor Marcello Mastroianni wears a dark colored polo shirt with a white suit. His single-breasted suit jacket has two buttons, jetted pockets, and notch lapels. The top-most button is fastened but the bottom one is not. The bottom-most button is far from the buttonhole.

caption: Someone recently asked me what's the point of having two or three buttons on a tailored jacket if the bottom-most button isn't meant to be fastened? It's easier to understand style if you think of it in terms of social language, not purely as function. Let me give you some examples. üßµ

alt_text: The image displays a video configuration screen from a software interface. The layout is divided into sections, each set against a blue background. At the top, there is a horizontal menu bar with options like "GAME," "CONFIG," "CHEAT," "NETPLAY," and "MISC." Below this, two tabs titled "MODES" and "FILTERS" are visible, with the "MODES" tab selected. The left side of the screen lists various resolution options in a vertical column, with a pink highlight over the "800X600" resolution. To the right of the resolutions, letters such as "DSRW" and "F" indicate different settings, explained in the "LEGEND" section on the right side. The legend clarifies the meaning of each letter: "D" for allow filters, "S" for stretch, "R" for keep 8:7 ratio, "W" for windowed, and "F" for fullscreen. Towards the bottom, the currently selected resolution is displayed as "CURRENT: 800X600." There's also a "CUSTOM" setting feature with "SET" buttons and numeric fields showing "640" by "480."

alt_text: A mock screenshot from the artist's sadly fake monster dating sim, "A Year In Endelochia", with a typical dating sim UI including the location, time & date (The Hog & Bucket Pub: Night; Late Winter), buttons for in-game functions (Diary, Status, Contacts, Travel, Settings, Save & Exit) and a panel for the scene's story text & buttons for the player's choices. A colour digital drawing shows the current scene, in which two demons, Settou & the would-be Player Character, are chatting in a seedy pub. Settou is big and thickly muscled with long, thick, shaggy white hair, blood red skin & two tall, black horns on his head. He has a prominent nose & thick jaw, and two small, upwards-facing tusks. The young PC is much smaller & more lightly built, having a short coat of sky blue fur with dark purple leopard spots covering his body. He has short, scruffy lavender hair, a long, tufted tail & digitigrade legs with cat-like paws, and is heavily pregnant. Settou is crouching next to him as he sits at the bar, one hand lightly on the PC's belly and the other arm resting on the bar behind him, and is smiling at him warmly as the PC leans back on the bar, looking startled. The scene text reads: This is the first time you've visited the Hog & Bucket since last Spring, and perhaps you shouldn't be surprised to find Settou here. He's delighted to see you, eager to make up for lost time, and clearly enamoured with the way your body has changed since your last meeting. Once again, he's friendly and gentle, and very, very handsy. However, once again you're distracted during your conversation; it's only for a moment and it disappears as quickly as it came, but a distinct cramping sensation interrupts you mid-thought. What was that? Was it anything? It might be nothing, but then again, it might not be. What now? The PC's options read as follows: Tell Settou about it. Tell Settou you want to fuck. Keep chatting. Try to flirt. Tell Settou to go away. Leave. The "Leave" option is highlighted.

caption: Vox Marauder Special
alt_text:
You may have heard of the Fender Marauder, a fancy offset model Fender prototyped in the 1960s and released in 2011. You may have even heard of the Gibson Marauder, a Les Paul-looking Fender competitor with a bolt-on neck from the 1970s. I bet you haven't heard of the Vox Marauder, though. I know I hadn't until I found this yesterday.

 The Vox Marauder is a vaguely Fenderish solidbody electric with two pickups. The Special version (seen in this picture) has built-in battery-powered effects. There are six rectangular push buttons (Treble, Bass, Top Boost, Mid Boost, Fuzz, and Repeat) a 3-way rotary switch controlling a mid boost, a 3-way blade pickup switch, a knob for the fuzz, a knob for the repeater, and a volume control with an on-off switch for the effects. This guitar also has a trem with a Telecaster-style ashtray.

Top left, a remote, with volume, chancel changers, keypad, trackpad, mouse buttons, and function buttons; there's a battery hatch at the bottom. Top right, a slimline vertical tower with a round base, labeled 'INTERNET AQUOS'; there are media control buttons, a power button, a vertical DVD hatch, and a power light. alt_text:
Traditional art of Pok√©mon - reference sheet of a Raichu original character.
Title says "Rain the Raichu - OC / Pok√©sona of RaincoatRodent". The design is at the center - a Raichu wearing a yellow raincoat with three black buttons, two pockets, and black accents on the sleeves, pockets, and the edge of the raincoat and its hood, as well as a red scarf and an accessory resembling a sunflower (with two sunflowers, one on each side) on his tail.
On the left, there are two drawings of Rain at a 3/4 angle, described as "Main look: hood down, raincoat unbuttoned" and "Depending on the premise of the artwork, hood can be up, and / or raincoat can be buttoned up".
At the bottom, there's a reference for how the eyes should generally be drawn, described as "eye shape: slightly curved at top for most expressions," and examples of a happy, sad, and angry expression with those eyes.
In the top right, the clothing is shown: the yellow raincoat, at three different angles to show the opening for the tail at the bottom, and that the black accents are only on the outside parts of the raincoat, not on the inside; the red scarf; and the sunflower tail accessory, with two angles showing how it looks on the tail, and a demonstration of how it consists of two connected semicircle parts that clip around the tail.
Below, the colors present in the design are shown, with text next to the colors saying "regular Raichu colors (& fur patterns) under raincoat" and "raincoat, scarf, flower (Pikachu color scheme)".
Below that, there's text saying "Personality: Whatever you imagine my personality to be... I'm curious what other people might think I'm like!"

caption: New introduction post! My name is Reef, and I'm an Arachtoy - a giant, inflatable spider! Specifically, I'm a Scubarachnid, made for diving deep into the ocean! I love transformations, squeakiness, bugs, and being silly and light-hearted! My dream is to find treasure in the seafloor! Check my ref!
alt_text:
A reference sheet of Reef, a pooltoy spider, or Arachtoy. Pronouns are any/all. Reef is depicted as an eight-legged, primarily red being made of squeaky vinyl. They have bright yellow antennae and distinctive goggles on their face with big shiny green simple ovular eyes, along with a set of shiny yellow mandibles around their mouth. The goggles are rimmed with pink, and have an attached pink and purple snorkel. Reef has inflatable air valves on both their lower chest and on the tip of their abdomen. Their eight legs are all wearing pink and purple pirate-style boots, with yellow buttons and buckles. On their back is a sonar thorax-pack that detects treasure and regulates their airflow so that they can become denser to sink into water. Purple tubes come off of it, attaching to the large inflated abdomen. The abdomen itself is styled like a torpedo, with white stripes and yellow fins decorating it. Between two sets of fins is written Reef's designation code, TS-38. TS stands for Torpedo Spider, by the way. Besides the main pose, the refsheet also depicts a detailed shot of the sonar thorax-pack, a boot, and an overhead view of Reef. The main colors are depicted on the side as a palette, styled like bubbles.

This art was made by Plushiespork, who can be found at least on bluesky and furaffinity!

caption: Another oldie I can use for the #fatfurgala - my boys dressed in fancy gold as the Three of Cups tarot card!
alt_text:
Shiny gold tarot card of the Three of Cups, with stylized black and gold trim around the edge of the card. Simmy, Copper, and Wolfie are all dressed in fancy clothes and squished into the rectangular space of the card. 

Simmy is in the front with a gold-and-orange striped zip-up jacket and button fastener neckline, with a white-and-gold checkerboard pattern coat with gold label buttons. He holds two of the cups and has a goofy tongue-out expression (as a wuff is wont to do~)

Copper is behind him, wearing golden bracelets along with a regal-looking chocolate-brown-and-garnet striped shirt with gold adornments, covered by a brown robe with a crashing wave design and gold trim, squeezed by a gold belt. His clothes struggle to contain his tummy and a bit is exposed at the bottom. He looks smug and stoned, like a Coppy does. His paw rests on Simmy's upheld cup as he stands above the smaller wolf.

Wolfie is in the back, missing his signature trucker hat but adorned with a wave-striped white-and-gold coat with gold chain across the chest. He wears nothing else, leaving his very fluffy chest out. His face is particularly wide and soft, and he looks down with golden hues in his eyes and a hungry-yet-dopey expression. Biggest of the three, he looms over the other boys, cup in one paw while the other paw rests on Copper's shoulder.

caption: Roland G-707 and GR-700
alt_text:
The Roland G-707 was a wild-looking synth controller guitar. It's shaped like a reverse Flying V on the top half and a big triangle on the bottom half. There's also a plastic stabilizer bar running from the upper horn to the reverse 6-in-line headstock that aids in tracking stability.

Theoretically, you could plug this guitar into a normal amp and use its two humbuckers, volume and tone controls, and 3-way switch to rock out, but that's boring. What you want to do with something this wild is hook up the GR-700 guitar synth (with a MASSIVE 24-pin connector) and make weird noises! To help you do that, there are knobs for balance, cutoff frequency, LFO modulation, and resonance. There's also a floating trem.

caption:
üëá 

I really think a lot of this could have been avoided if we had compulsory international service for a year after high school - like army style, but ‚Äúget the fuck out of the country Timmy and eat them apples for a while‚Äù
alt_text:
The sheer prosperity of the country could be breathtaking. I had just come back from Senegal when the Guardian sent me on assignment to rust belt Ohio, during the first stirrings of Trumpism, back in 2015. I was there to report on the growing swell of populism by way of the postindustrial immiseration of middle America.
I was stopping for gas on the way to a rally, and at the station they were selling a hotdog with as much chilli and cheese as you liked for $1.99. The chilli and cheese came out of the wall. You pressed two buttons, one for chilli and one for cheese.
On the streets of Dakar, children hawk packs of peanuts and plastic bags of clean water on the street, and I wondered if you could even explain to them that there existed a place, on the same earth, where chilli and liquid cheese came out of a wall, and you could have as much of it as you liked for the equivalent of 20 minutes' work at the minimum wage, and that some of the people in that place considered themselves so hard done by that their resentful fury threatened the political order, that they just wanted to burn it all down.

alt_text:
Further, two of Apple‚Äôs restrictions are explicitly at odds with the Injunction. The
Injunction prevented Apple from stopping developers from ‚Äúincluding in their apps and their
metadata buttons, external links, or other calls to action that direct customers to purchasing
mechanisms, in addition to‚Äù IAP. Apple resorts to dictionaries (see Dkt. No. 1324 at 15‚Äì16) to
argue that it no longer categorically prohibits developers from using buttons or other calls to
action.66 While perhaps literally true, the gamesmanship abounds as the business documents
reveal the true motive (and do not rely on dictionaries).
For button styles, Apple limits developers to what Apple calls the ‚Äúplain‚Äù button style‚Äî
essentially just a hyperlink‚Äîbecause Apple does not want the developers to use the more effective
‚Äúbutton.‚Äù A more effective button would increase competition. (See Feb. 2025 Tr. 1212:9‚Äì
1213:22 (Schiller).) Similarly, Apple limits calls to action to five, narrowly cabined templates.
(See CX-3.5.) Nowhere does the Court authorize those limitations. At a minimum, the Court
need not decide whether these restrictions alone violate the Injunction, because Apple has violated
the central mandate of this Court‚Äôs orders: that Apple not foreclose competitive alternatives to
IAP.67

caption: Here are higher-res scans of the first super Famicom announcement from Nov. 21, 1988, a full *two years* before the SFC finally hit store shelves in Japan.  (I believe it's still necessary to bake an explanation into the scan itself, so I've done that.)
alt_text:
Image from Famicom Tsushin, 12/23/1988. Headline (on previous page) reads: "The SFC is completely incompatible with the Famicom!!"
The page explains how the newly-announced Super Famicom has no backwards-compatibility with the old Famicom. The SFC will, however, have an A/V input on the back which will accept the A/V signals of the "Famicom Adaptor", the redesigned Famicom with A/V outputs.
The image shows off the standard controller ports of the SFC, its expansion port on the front which would be moved to the bottom, an RGB multi out on the back which would get a redesign, and three features that would eventually get removed entirely: A/V input jacks on the back (for pass-through), a pass-through switch on the top, and a headphone jack with volume dial on the side.

caption:
Japanese leather firefighter's hood, ca. 1850-1900. This belonged to a woman of the samurai class, and was probably not actively used to fight fires.
Ref T.64-1909, V & A Museum.
alt_text: Fire hood (kaji zukin) of gold-lacquered leather and embroidered woollen cloth. Rounded and curved in shape. Three silk-cr√™pe bands run round the base, coloured red, white and purple crossed obliquely by gilt threads. These terminate at the back in a bow fastened by gilt-edged chrysanthemum and hang down behind as three pairs of streamers. The front is decorated with a piece of red cloth of wavy outline edged with silk and gilt braid. The deep neck-flaps of red cloth, lined with green satin, are embroidered with butterflies in green and white silk. The edges are covered with gilt braid. Decorated on both sides with the crest of the Honda family. The crest occupies the middle of either neck-flap and is embroidered in white silk. The deeper shoulder-flaps of purple cloth, lined with green satin, are furnished with two buttons attached to brown silk cords, and with two loops of the same material. The patterns on the shoulder-flaps, in gilt-thread and coloured silks, consist of chrysanthemums and bamboo stems. Furnished with a couple of tying strings of purple silk-cr√™pe stuffed with cotton wool.

caption: Vance has Nem by the leesh once again, putting the big guy front-and-center for another bedside photoshoot. This time around, they've listened to the requests of their fans.
alt_text:
Nem is face-first in a big, pillowy, yellow snake sole - just licking and huffing away. Just out of view, he's stroking himself at top speed.
Vance tugs him along by a leash, softly groping at his breast via his toes.

Kenta (the Zangoose tasked with lighting and shooting,) and is mildly concerned by Nem's mad mumbling.
"Uh. Is he okay..?"

"He gets like this pretty often. Best to let it ride out," replies Vance. He gives the leash a playful tug.

Kenta could almost feel his fur stand up. As usual, given the generations-long tension between the two mons.
"'Often,' huh..?"

Vance softly hisses, "At leassst when he's on-camera."

Panel 2: POV of the other camera. It's focused on Nem's rear, with his sweaty feet foremost (of course.)
Vance continues, "Speaking of cameras, how's the lighting back there?"

Kenta was a little baffled by how normal this sounded...
"You're way too casual..."

"I sssaid I do this often~," raises Vance, in an almost sing-song tone.

Kenta lets out an almost disappointed sigh.
"You'd better pay me for doing this."
Continued in image 2.

caption: In fact, even buttons can signal one's position in the British foot guards. Look at these uniforms. Seemingly identical right? But take a look at the subtle differences in the way the buttons are placed on the jacket sleeve cuffs. They signal one's regiment.
alt_text: An illustrated chart showing the four regiments in the British foot guards. The Grenadier Guards have a uniform distinguished by four buttons equally spaced apart on the jacket cuff and a white plume on the left side of the cap. The Colestream Guards have four buttons in a pairing of two, each pair slightly spaced apart, and then a red plume on the right side of the cap. The Scots Guards have buttons in threes and no plume. The Irish Guards have buttons in fours and a blue plume on the right side of the cap. The Welsh Guards have buttons in fives and and white and green plume on the left side of the cap.

caption: The Minor Headdress, known as the Shu'shut, is consistently worn by Kalasha women of Pakistan. A woman only removes it when going to bed at night. Kupas are worn over the Shu'shut and hold significant importance in Kalasha culture. They are worn during all major ceremonies.
alt_text: The major Headdress: Kupas -  Kalasha women wear one of the most elaborate and ornate serpent-style headdresses called Kupas. Kupas is the major headdress of women. Kupas is a woolen headdress hanging down the back, covered with eight to ten rows of cowrie shells or chakash (cakas), with two rows folded upward on each side of the Kupas, and other tail decorations,

alt_text:
Alastor from Hazbin Hotel is dressed up in his official Ace Pride vest and pants from his official plushie, Pride edition. The vest has the Ace Flag colours of black, grey, white, and purple. The vest being mostly purple with three other colours as thick stripes at the top, and grey buttons. His pants are dark purple with lighter purple stripes. His dress shirt is white with the sleeves rolled up to his elbows. He wears fingerless gloves that have a black cuff and the rest of the glove is grey. Around his neck is a black bowtie.

Alastor's hair is tied up in a short ponytail, his ears are turned back, and atop of his head is a big white top hat with a black and grey ribbon tie around the top part of the hat and purple is on the underside of the brim. On the top part of the hat in purple lettering it says, "I'm the Birthday Deer!" There is a small demon yellow duck perched on a bouncy spring that has black and purple horns and is wearing a grey and black bowtie.

Lucifer is wearing a pink hoody, with rolled up sleeves, that has a logo design of a butter duck sitting atop of a stack of pancakes that reads, "Who Wants Pancakes?". His turtle neck shirt is visible underneath the hoody and it is striped with the genderqueer flag colours of white, purple, and green. Atop of his head is a small white top hat that has a bright rainbow ribbon around it and text that reads, "LuLu World". On a bouncy spring is a yellow demon duck sporting purple horns and a purple bowtie.

Lucifer has one arm slung behind Alastor and his hand resting on his shoulder as he raises his other hand and snapping his fingers with a flurry of sparkly gold magic that arcs up and around Alastor. Lucifer has a big wide exuberant smile as he looks up at Alastor who has a surprised but slightly nervous look. One eyebrow is raised as he has a small smile with only one fang showing. His hands are raised as if unsure if he should relax into Lucifer's friendly but excited gesture.

caption: There's something about the red ones.
alt_text: A three-component computer setup, all in the matte red that made Sharp's comptuers distrinct. Top left, a remote, with volume, chancel changers, keypad, trackpad, mouse buttons, and function buttons; there's a battery hatch at the bottom. Top right, a slimline vertical tower with a round base, labeled 'INTERNET AQUOS'; there are media control buttons, a power button, a vertical DVD hatch, and a power light. Bottom, a slimline PC keybaord; the full set of usual IBM keys is present, but the case is scrunched to fit the arrow keys between the tenkey and the keyboard, and the usual navigation keys are presented in a slim strip, in order to fit in one last column of multimedia keys and a two-button trackpad on the right hand side.

caption:
meet the terminal emulator wizardzines.com/comics/meet-...

(from The Secret Rules of the Terminal, out now!  (wizardzines.com/zines/termin...)
alt_text:
your terminal emulator has two main jobs

    turn your actions (typing & clicking) into bytes and send them
    receive bytes and display them visually

Illustration of a terminal emulator, with a winking cursor face, and a program, represented by a box with a smiley face. The program has a heart above it, and there are arrows going back and forth between them labelled ‚Äúbytes‚Äù
a little bit of history

it‚Äôs called an ‚Äúemulator‚Äù because in the 80s a ‚Äúterminal‚Äù was a separate machine from the computer

Illustration of a bulky old monitor, with a keyboard attached with a spiral cord, and a wire running to a panl of buttons and displays, labelld ‚Äúmainframe‚Äù. There are arrows going back and forth between them labelled ‚Äúbytes‚Äù

We still use the same 80s protocol!
what are these ‚Äúbytes‚Äù?

the bytes are either:

    text (like cat blah.txt)
    escape codes (for example to tell the terminal what colour to display the text in)
    control characters example Ctrl+C is the byte 3)

it‚Äôs in charge of copy and paste

your terminal emulator lets you select text and copy/paste it (usually with Ctrl+Shift+C (Linux) or Cmd+C (Mac))

(copy & paste tips on page 18!)
it manages colours and fonts!

some terminal emulators come with a big theme library of different colourschemes!

if yours doesn‚Äôt, this site has colourschemes for many terminal emulators: iterm2colorschemes.com
fun fact: how Ctrl-X gets translated to bytes

Ctrl-A => 1
Ctrl-B => 2
...
Ctrl-Z => 26

Ctrl is the only modifier key I trust in the terminal, all of the others can work differently depending on the situation

caption: Exciting news, everyone! As Conjured Ink nears its first beta, we'd like to share with you our roadmap of updates for the next two quarters. These quality of life and system changes will help pave the way for what we hope to become: a home for your incredible works! Thank you!
alt_text:
An image on a sky blue background, with black ink drops and bubbles all across it. There are words in each of the bubbles and a title across the top which reads "Conjured Ink Development Road Map".

In the first stage, which will be completed by December of 2025, there are five categories: customization, store, compliance, communication, and miscellaneous. 

Under customization: light mode/dark mode, embedded buy buttons, custom theme uploads, and custom domain support.

Under store: single payment processor support, transaction history, cart management, custom products, and multi-currency support.

Under compliance: geoblocking by IP adress (for NSFW).

Under communication: multi language support, custom blog pages, and newsletters (external).

Under miscellaneous: backup and restore data.

caption: Sharp Internet AQUOS PC-AX120V (2007)
alt_text: A three-component computer setup, all in the matte red that made Sharp's comptuers distrinct. Top left, a remote, with volume, chancel changers, keypad, trackpad, mouse buttons, and function buttons; there's a battery hatch at the bottom. Top right, a slimline vertical tower with a round base, labeled 'INTERNET AQUOS'; there are media control buttons, a power button, a vertical DVD hatch, and a power light. Bottom, a slimline PC keybaord; the full set of usual IBM keys is present, but the case is scrunched to fit the arrow keys between the tenkey and the keyboard, and the usual navigation keys are presented in a slim strip, in order to fit in one last column of multimedia keys and a two-button trackpad on the right hand side.

caption: spy vs spy redux (2023)
alt_text:
An old man with a long pointed nose sits in an a chair smoking a cigarette. He is wearing a tank top, which bends over his gut. His hair is thin, his hair has liver spots. 
He is the White Spy from Spy Vs Spy, but ancient now.

Behind him, a gun clicks.

"You know why I'm here old man."

"Speak for yourself. The war is over. It's time to come in from the cold."

The Black Spy holds the gun feebly.  

"I took a pledge. Same as you. And I will do what I must to keep it."

"then I will as well. You know how this ends just as I do."

Suddenly, violently, a bowling ball falls from the ceiling, crashing into the Black Spy's head. Blood splatters from his shattered skull. 

The White Spy looks resigned, his hand on a the trigger of a button, tethered to the unseen machine that dropped the ball.

"After all these years, I'm still asking myself, is a flag worth dying for?"

The White Spy makes a half hearted V with his fingers.

"Guess you got your answer old man. And I got mine."

A screenshot of Red Star OS 3.0, which looks strikingly similar to Mac OS X (Snow) Leopard, but with a slightly different theme, a green wallpaper, and mostly green icons. The menu bar has a red star where the Apple logo would be on Mac OS X. The OS is in Korean.
Prominently featured are an about window resembling the "About this Mac" window on older versions of Mac OS X, a system information viewer that resembles the Mac OS X System Profiler, and a file manager that looks near-identical to the Finder from Mac OS X Leopard and Snow Leopard, with the only real differences being the lack of a Cover Flow button and the use of green icons. The file manager features a Columns view, which also looks near-identical to the Finder, and a bottom path bar.

caption: The IBM JX (1984)
alt_text: A three-piece desktop computer.  Up top is a black CRT, with a single red power button.  The pizzabox style case features two 3.25" drives, a recessed red power switch, and an unlabeled future expansion port.  The front of the case seems to slide off entirely, which would allow the top to hinge up and off, like their competitor Apple.  The keyboard, itself, is black in the familiar IBM layout, with one addition:  a raised ridge, where a student might rest a pencil.

DuckAssist BETA
DuckAssist is an optional feature in our search results that can anonymously generate answers to search queries. To do this, it scans the web for relevant content and then uses AI-powered natural language technology to generate a brief answer based on relevant information found. DuckAssist responses always link directly to one or two sources, citing where the answer came from, so you can easily go and get more detailed information. It‚Äôs important to remember that responses are auto-generated from cited sources and based on crawling the web.

DuckAssist cannot answer follow-up questions, however, we also offer DuckDuckGo AI Chat, which is a private AI-powered chat service that supports chat models from OpenAI, and Anthropic, and more.

Phrasing your search as a question and in a complete sentence makes DuckAssist more likely to appear automatically and often yields better answers. To turn it off and hide the Assist button visit DuckAssist Settings.

caption: Wearing another Takato Yamamoto dress today‚ú®serving modesty, softness, and goth intensity.
alt_text:
The image depicts Nani wearing a striking dress that prominently features the artwork of Japanese artist Takato Yamamoto. The dress is designed as a button-up shirtdress with a tailored fit, long sleeves, and a high collar. The fabric is predominantly black, creating a dramatic backdrop that allows the intricate, colorful artwork to stand out vividly.

The artwork on the dress blends surrealism with gothic and erotic themes, which are hallmarks of Yamamoto‚Äôs ‚ÄúHeisei Estheticism‚Äù style. The design features delicate, detailed linework and soft pastel tones, particularly shades of pink and ivory, offset by black and grey elements. The motifs include roses, a central female figure with an introspective expression, lace patterns, and skeletal elements, such as a human skull. These elements evoke a mix of beauty and mortality, a duality frequently explored in Yamamoto‚Äôs works.

Takato Yamamoto is celebrated for his intricate and hauntingly beautiful illustrations that fuse traditional Japanese aesthetics with modern gothic and macabre themes. His art is deeply influenced by the Ukiyo-e woodblock print tradition and incorporates eroticism, mythology, and death into visually arresting compositions. His 2003 book, Ribs of a Hermaphrodite, is one of his seminal works, showcasing his mastery of blending the sensual with the grotesque. The collection explores themes of androgyny, identity, and the fragility of human existence through ethereal, otherworldly imagery. His work often portrays figures entwined with nature and symbols of decay, suggesting a cycle of life and death.

This dress effectively transforms Yamamoto‚Äôs artwork into wearable art, making it a bold statement piece that juxtaposes the ephemeral beauty of high fashion with the timeless depth of fine art. The wearer embodies both sophistication and edge, perfectly complementing the layered symbolism in Yamamoto‚Äôs style.

caption: In 1958 Bill Buckley was desperate to find more subscribers for his fledgling ‚Äúconservative‚Äù magazine. And so he reached out to the White Citizens Councils (which had formed to oppose Brown v Board) to get their mailing list. Hunting where the anti-14th Amendment ducks were.
alt_text:
July 28, 1958
1999
Dear Mr. McFadden:
I am thoroughly ashamed of myself. The fact is that I clean forgot about writing you in zeference to blis business of our out-of-State subscription list. Immediately after I talked with you by telephone the other day, I spoke with our Executive Vice-President, who in turn made inquiry of the Cirmlation Department. It appears that it would be almost impossible to isolate the out-of-State subscribers to either The News Leader of The Times-Dispatch, These things are li-worked by some sort of train route classification, which includes both Virginia subacribers and out-of-State subscribers on down the line, and it is not possible simply to push a button labelled "Indiana" and have a machine cough up the names and addresses of 22 subscribers in Indiana. I should have passed this information on to you a couple of weeks ago, and I'm awfully sorry that it slipped my mind.
I did write Bill Buckley, however, on the matter of the Citizens' Council mailing list. As I told him, Bill Simmons visited me here in Richmond in late June or early July, and volunteered to get together with you folke on some mutually acceptable plan. I believe he told me that he has upwards of 60, 000 names on his mailing list, and he has no objection to making these available to you. Obviously, however, this is a matter for you to work out directly with him. My suggestion would be that you write him at 1014 Plasa Building, Jackson, Mississippl, and see what might be arranged.
Faithfully yours,
James J. Kilpatrick
Editor
Mr. J. P. McFadden
National Review
211 East 37th Street
New York 16, New York

caption:
Tech's decay is a class issue. The bestselling laptop on Amazon when I wrote this piece was a $238 Acer laptop with a crippled operating system, one so slow that it couldn‚Äôt cleanly render much of Windows Home. Millions of people use laptops like these.
www.wheresyoured.at/never-forgive-them/
alt_text:
I‚Äôll give you a more direct example.

On November 21, I purchased the bestselling laptop from Amazon ‚Äî a $238 Acer Aspire 1 with a four-year-old Celeron N4500 Processor, 4GB of DDR4 RAM, and 128GB of slow eMMC storage (which is, and I‚Äôm simplifying here, though not by much, basically an SD card soldered to the computer‚Äôs motherboard). Affordable and under-powered, I‚Äôd consider this a fairly representative sample of how millions of people interact with the internet. 

I believe it‚Äôs also a powerful illustration of the damage caused by the Rot Economy, and the abusive, exploitative way in which the tech industry treats people at scale.

It took 1 minute and 50 seconds from hitting the power button for the laptop to get to the setup screen. It took another minute and a half to connect and begin downloading updates, which took several more minutes. After that, I was faced with a licensing agreement where I agreed to binding arbitration to use Windows, a 24 second pause, and then got shown a screen of different ‚Äúways I could unlock my Microsoft experience,‚Äù with animations that shuddered and jerked violently.

caption: The advice On Here about just doing a smol but earnest select committee submission is very good, but I regret to inform that I have done a Hundy Poast about the Treaty Principles Bill
alt_text:
The bill as drafted is, in the simplest terms, a lie.

It asserts a fictive "official" interpretation of Te Tiriti that differs in important ways from the really-existing meaning of the Treaty. It asserts the ACT party's view of three Treaty principles synthesised loosely from the three articles of the Treaty as if these are the single true and historically correct interpretation of the Treaty and its principles. Essentially this bill amounts to an attempt by Parliament to instate ACT's idiosyncratic interpretation of the Treaty's meaning over the entire body of existing knowledge about the Treaty, as the politically correct state-approved interpretation, in an Orwellian attempt to control the past by controlling the present.

In doing so, the bill ignores almost two centuries of real history, including extensive breaches of the Treaty's plain text and its principles in any form. It seeks to sweep away the deep historical analysis that exists about what the Treaty meant to those who drafted it, those who signed it, and those who administered it after signing. It seeks to erase the five decades of bipartisan law, policy, jurisprudence, and institutional norms that have accrued since the passage of the Treaty of Waitangi Act 1975 and which currently govern this interface between the Crown & MƒÅori.

The bill seeks to reduce the complex reality of our really-existing history to a set of three partisan Just-So Stories about what the Treaty "truly" means in its essence. The three principles derived in this way have been widely criticised as false or misleading by historians, legal experts, translators, and essentially everyone with more than a trivial working understanding of the Treaty's genuine history and jurisprudence. In addition, the bill asserts that this fictive interpretation of the Treaty has always been so -- as if the disputes about what the Treaty means or ought to mean had never occurred. It is an attempt to settle history by declaring victory over it.

	OpenAI says it has found evidence that Chinese artificial intelligence start-up DeepSeek used the US company‚Äôs proprietary models to train its own open-source competitor, as concerns grow over a potential breach of intellectual property.

The San Francisco-based ChatGPT maker told the Financial Times it had seen some evidence of ‚Äúdistillation‚Äù, which it suspects to be from DeepSeek.

The technique is used by developers to obtain better performance on smaller models by using outputs from larger, more capable ones, allowing them to achieve similar results on specific tasks at a much lower cost.

Distillation is a common practice in the industry but the concern was that DeepSeek may be doing it to build its own rival model, which is a breach of OpenAI‚Äôs terms of service.

‚ÄúThe issue is when you [take it out of the platform and] are doing it to create your own model for your own purposes,‚Äù said one person close to OpenAI.

caption: I am going to start writing about the practical issues with products I regularly use - such as Riverside.fm, the "best" podcasting software that has a chaotic, illogical user interface that they constantly change. The only reason Riverside is the best is that the competition sucks more.
alt_text:
Let me give you a current example. Riverside makes arguably the easiest-to-use podcasting software - it works in a browser, it records reliably, it's easy to invite people - but inexplicably moves buttons around every once in a while. It used to be that I could just hit the "plus" button to make a new recording - but now I have to, for no reason, scroll down a list of already-existing studios (which is what they call recordings) that are completely out of order and hit "new studio."  On hitting that button, nothing appears to happen - because Riverside's new UI means that they want you to hit "plan," "record," "upload" or "edit," the latter of which allows them to sell their higher-priced subscriptions.

Riverside has changed this interface at least twice in the last year. Another cool thing that they do is if you want to download all of the audio files from an episode, you have to hit "export only," which brings you to an extremely awkward-to-use user interface full of other buttons. For some reason, if you hit the "download cloud" button, it'll download a video of the entire session immediately. 

Nothing in Riverside is organized logically. "Projects" are meant to be, I assume, where you can group recordings, except you do not appear to be able to move things into them, and on creating a "Project" you have to create - by scheduling or recording - something inside it as a means of saving it. "Studios" are, it seems, where you record stuff. You can no longer, as a result of recent UI changes, see a full list of studios - you have to scroll through them. A logical way would be to have "projects" that have within them distinct recording sessions, and a drag-and-drop interface.  

Riverside is widely respected as "the best" podcast software. I pay for it not because it's good - I regularly find it genuinely, upsettingly annoying to use - but because services like Zencaster and Squadcast are markedly worse.

caption: Hubble Sees A Smiling Lens - From Goddard Space Flight Center - https://flic.kr/p/qQTe4J
alt_text:
In the center of this image, taken with the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope, is the galaxy cluster SDSS J1038+4849 ‚Äî and it seems to be smiling.

You can make out its two orange eyes and white button nose. In the case of this ‚Äúhappy face‚Äù, the two eyes are very bright galaxies and the misleading smile lines are actually arcs caused by an effect known as strong gravitational lensing.

Galaxy clusters are the most massive structures in the Universe and exert such a powerful gravitational pull that they warp the spacetime around them and act as cosmic lenses which can magnify, distort and bend the light behind them. This phenomenon, crucial to many of Hubble‚Äôs discoveries, can be explained by Einstein‚Äôs theory of general relativity.

In this special case of gravitational lensing, a ring ‚Äî known as an Einstein Ring ‚Äî is produced from this bending of light, a consequence of the exact and symmetrical alignment of the source, lens and observer and resulting in the ring-like structure we see here.

Hubble has provided astronomers with the tools to probe these massive galaxies and model their lensing effects, allowing us to peer further into the early Universe than ever before. This object was studied by Hubble‚Äôs Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2 (WFPC2) and Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3) as part of a survey of strong lenses.

A version of this image was entered into the Hubble‚Äôs Hidden Treasures image processing competition by contestant Judy Schmidt.

Image Credit: NASA/ESA

My suggestion was quite simple: Put that needed code number in a little capsule, and then implant that capsule right next to the heart of a volunteer. The volunteer would carry with him a big, heavy butcher knife as he accompanied the President. If ever the President wanted to fire nuclear weapons, the only way he could do so would be for him first, with his own hands, to kill one human being. The President says, "George, I'm sorry but tens of millions must die." He has to look at someone and realize what death is‚Äîwhat an innocent death is. Blood on the White House carpet. It's reality brought home.

When I suggested this to friends in the Pentagon they said, "My God, that's terrible. Having to kill someone would distort the President's judgment. He might never push the button."

‚Äî‚ÄäRoger Fisher, Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, March 1981

caption:
Two incredible antiquities from #Pompeii - and they're surprisingly related. On the left, a spectacular cobalt glass cameo amphora with Dionysian scenes. On the right, one of four mosaic columns that supported a pergola in the garden of the Villa of the Mosaic Columns. üßµüè∫ 1/ #ancientbluesky

üì∏ me
alt_text:
This cobalt blue glass amphora is a masterpiece of the cameo technique. It has two ribbed handles and a tapered bottom ending in a 'button'. The belly is almost entirely decorated with the carved outer layer of white opaque glass, cut away to create scenes and decorative elements whose theme is of Dionysiac inspiration, against the dark blue underlayer of transparent glass. The figured scenes are under the handles while on the front and back of the vessel are plant and animal decorations. The figurative portions show erotes that indulge in Dionysian activities; on one side, an erote is half lying on a bed while another plays the lyre, while two other erotes stand on a pedestal, harvest grapes. On the opposite side, two erotes play musical instruments, one on the syrinx, the other on the flute, sitting on high pedestals. Two other erotes engage in different activities. The decoration of the two sides - identical in their composition - depict a large mask decorated with vine leaves from which two large grape vines full of leaves and clusters of grapes emerge; in the center two vine volutes bear fantasy flowers and birds. In the lower register, under the ground line, is a frieze representing a pastoral scene. Goats and sheep graze in a landscape planted with trees.

From the Tomb of the Blue Glass Vase, Pompeii.

caption: Hubble Sees A Smiling Lens - From Goddard Space Flight Center - https://flic.kr/p/qQTe4J
alt_text:
In the center of this image, taken with the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope, is the galaxy cluster SDSS J1038+4849 ‚Äî and it seems to be smiling.

You can make out its two orange eyes and white button nose. In the case of this ‚Äúhappy face‚Äù, the two eyes are very bright galaxies and the misleading smile lines are actually arcs caused by an effect known as strong gravitational lensing.

Galaxy clusters are the most massive structures in the Universe and exert such a powerful gravitational pull that they warp the spacetime around them and act as cosmic lenses which can magnify, distort and bend the light behind them. This phenomenon, crucial to many of Hubble‚Äôs discoveries, can be explained by Einstein‚Äôs theory of general relativity.

In this special case of gravitational lensing, a ring ‚Äî known as an Einstein Ring ‚Äî is produced from this bending of light, a consequence of the exact and symmetrical alignment of the source, lens and observer and resulting in the ring-like structure we see here.

Hubble has provided astronomers with the tools to probe these massive galaxies and model their lensing effects, allowing us to peer further into the early Universe than ever before. This object was studied by Hubble‚Äôs Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2 (WFPC2) and Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3) as part of a survey of strong lenses.

A version of this image was entered into the Hubble‚Äôs Hidden Treasures image processing competition by contestant Judy Schmidt.

Image Credit: NASA/ESA

alt_text:
Dear Madam:
The Celsius network promised yield and custodianship of coins and never let on to the fact there was risk involved in the company. The terms of service changed at one point and there was no way to not accept them to access your account. I was suspicious of the change (and the button did not offer decline on the app) but allowed Celsius to hold my assets nonetheless.
I was a teacher for over a decade and invested the majority of my earnings into the account and lost over 70% of them. The mental anguish has been awful and caused me depression that I am still dealing with on all levels. No matter how hard I work it will take decades to make up the loss from the Celsius network and by then I will be well into my 70s.
I pray for all the victims of this network and hope justice will be served in the months ahead.
Adam Vigor

caption:
I'm tired of fielding the same half-assed critiques of my work, so I've condensed my answers into one helpful section - no, the cost of inference isn't going down, no, OpenAI isn't growth stage, no, it isn't like the early days of the internet. Come at me.
www.wheresyoured.at/reality-check/
alt_text:
Forgive Me I'm Going To Be A Little Rude

In fact, you know what, let me just sit down and go through the critiques one-by-one. Some of you are going to say I'm being rude to these people and it weakens my analysis, to which I respond "kiss my entire ass." I can beat you to death with the truth while making fun of you for believing stupid things.

    The costs of inference are coming down: Source? Because it sure seems like they're increasing for OpenAI, and they're effectively the entire userbase of the generative AI industry! 
        But DeepSeek‚Ä¶ No, my sweet idiot child. DeepSeek is not OpenAI, and OpenAI‚Äôs latest models only get more expensive as time drags on. GPT-4.5 costs $75 per million input tokens, and $150 per million output tokens. And at the risk of repeating myself, OpenAI is effectively the generative AI industry ‚Äî at least, for the world outside China. 
    This is the company at its growth stage, it can simply "hit the button" and it'll all be profitable: You have the mind of a child! If this was the case, why would both Anthropic and OpenAI be losing so much money? Why are none of the hyperscalers making profit on AI? Why does nobody want to talk about the underlying economics?
    These are the early days of AI: Wrong! We have the entire tech industry and more money than has ever been invested into anything piled into generative AI and the result has been utterly mediocre. Nobody's making money but NVIDIA!
    They're already showing signs that it'll be powerful: No it's not! If it was there'd be people doing crazy, impressive things with it!
        But Ed, look at o-3: Oh you mean the new and extremely expensive reasoning model that hallucinates more somehow? Is that AGI? Is the AGI in the room with us now? Did it tell you it loved you? Did it tell you to leave your wife? I hope you're okay!!
    But Ed, really, it's the early days, it was just like this in the early days of the internet: No it wasn't! Read Jim Covello of Goldman Sachs' note ‚Ä¶

caption: RETVRN
alt_text:
SONY WM-51 (1987)

In 1987, Sony introduced the Walkman WM-51, which featured permanently attached headphones that could be wound and stored within the device.

This beautiful ‚Äúdesigner styled‚Äù model was based loosely around the mechanical parts of the WM-F107 ‚ÄúSolar Walkman‚Äù. Though not itself solar powered, it did include a novel feature, the headphones were permanently attached and could be rewound and stored in the machine using a large winding wheel at the rear. A second pair of headphones could also be connected, using a conventional socket.

As with the WM-F107, the mechanism was finely made and featured auto reverse. Dolby B NR was also included, and normal, chrome or metal tapes could be used. Power came either from a single ‚ÄúAA‚Äù cell or from a rechargeable battery, which was included with the Walkman, along with a special fast-charger. The cassette door was retained shut by a catch that was released by pressing the stop button for a second time, though this function could be locked using a slide switch next to the winding keys.

caption: Aria T. Matsui Signature bass
alt_text:
It's really frustrating when I find a guitar that's weird enough to post, but there aren't any full pictures of it available. That's when I've gotta get creative. 

This is part of page 12 of the 1995 catalog of Aria Pro guitars. On it are two bass guitars which were made by Aria's custom shop for bassist Tsunematsu Matsui. One is black with a white pickguard, and one is red with a white pickguard. 

The T. Matsui Signature bass is a version of the squared-off Flying V shape I've posted a few other times. The symmetrical pickguard starts at the V, narrows out at the bridge, splits and flares out to encircle the single P-pickup, and both sides curve back in by the neck. The only control you get is a on/off push button by the bridge, and the output jack is on the back of the bass.

Below the red bass are the specs for the model, and the top part of the background is a picture of good ol' T. Matsui himself playing one of the basses. Weirdly, the site where I found this catalog blurs out the faces of every person in every catalog.

caption: Why you might even say this is precisely what policies of ‚Äúinstitutional neutrality‚Äù and opposition to ‚Äúviewpoint discrimination‚Äù are design to foster. www.nytimes.com/2025/06/21/u...
alt_text:
Preston Damsky is a law student at the University of Florida. He is also a white nationalist and antisemite. Last fall, he took a seminar taught by a federal judge on ‚Äúoriginalism,‚Äù the legal theory favored by many conservatives that seeks to interpret the Constitution based on its meaning when it was adopted.

In his capstone paper for the class, Mr. Damsky argued that the framers had intended for the phrase ‚ÄúWe the People,‚Äù in the Constitution‚Äôs preamble, to refer exclusively to white people. From there, he argued for the removal of voting rights protections for nonwhites, and for the issuance of shoot-to-kill orders against ‚Äúcriminal infiltrators at the border.‚Äù

Subject: Support SB 627 ‚Äì End Secret Police Tactics in California

Dear [Assemblymember/Senator] [Last Name],

I‚Äôm writing as a concerned constituent to urge you to support SB 627, the No Secret Police Act, which would ban law enforcement officers in California from hiding their identities during operations.

This bill is a critical step toward restoring public trust, ensuring accountability, and protecting our communities from the rise of unmarked, masked agents conducting raids without identification. No one in a democracy should fear being approached by armed officers with no name, no badge, and no accountability.

SB 627 would:

- Require law enforcement to display visible identification (name or badge number),

- Limit the use of face coverings during enforcement actions.

- Preserve officer safety through reasonable exemptions (e.g. medical, SWAT, wildfire smoke).

California must not tolerate secretive policing tactics that mirror authoritarian regimes. We need legislation that reflects our values‚Äîtransparency, civil liberties, and public oversight.

I strongly urge you to vote YES on SB 627 and publicly support this bill.

Thank you.

Sincerely,
Your Full Name

alt_text:
A post with the title ‚ÄúLeft my card at home, but had $7 cash on me so l went to the coffee shop...‚Äù

... picked my drink and asked the cashier what was the largest size I could buy with $7.
"A venti is $7.01, so I can only do a grande." (Yes, this was the total after taxes were added.)
There was a take a penny leave a penny right between the two of us, so I told her l'd use one and ordered the venti.
She rang up a grande. I tried to correct her, multiple times, to no avail of course.
I'd put any amount of money on betting that she assumed I'd toss the change from the smaller drink in the tip jar.
I was already having quite the day so this ordeal was just the icing on the shit cake. I just didn't have it in me to argue anymore so I pocketed my change, which awarded me a shitty attitude while she walked off to make the drink.
l've been a barista (a real one, who actually grinds the espresso and packs and pours shots rather than just pushing a button). 13 years of perfecting coffee making and customer service. And if someone had come in, was a penny short and there was a tray of coins literally alloted for this exact situation, they'd be getting the fucking large that they ordered.

caption:
A while ago, we started a #FixItFriday tradition. We keep a running list - large & small, digital & analog, anything broken or annoying - and work on it together. 

Today's 30-second fix: to remove AI "preview" from search results, here's the setting for Chrome users: www.reddit.com/r/techsuppor...
alt_text:
Screenshot from Reddit. User is zensnapple, posting 6 months ago. 
Thread says
"How to turn off Google AI Overview in Chrome SOLVED
Open Chrome and put chrome://settings/searchEngines in the search box.
A tab will open which brings you to Search Engine > Manage Search Engines and Site Search.
Click on the Add button by the Site Search update. A box will open. Fill in the form with the following:
Name: AI Free Web
Shortcut: @web
URL: {google:baseURL}search?q=%s&udm=14
You‚Äôll now see AI Free Web in the list of search engines.
Click on the three stacked dots on the right side of AI Free Web on the list. Select Make Default.
From now on, google functions pretty much like it did back when it was good. Good luck out there."

caption: little modpack tutorial i made for friends. use it if you want to share your stuff w/ friends o7
alt_text:
Steps to set-up and export your mods.


Step 1 - (skip if you know which mods your chara uses): Open Penumbra and navigate to the On-Screen tab. You'll see what you're using on your char here. Note down the mods in green.

Step 2 - Note down a mod you want to pack all of your mods into. 
Example, using Aro's face mod as base, I'm going to pack his claws in. So I go into the Claws mod > Advanced editing > Merge mods

Repeat this step as many times as you need to.

	Sequoia Capital‚Äôs chief operating officer resigned over comments made by partner Shaun Maguire which she regarded as Islamophobic, as political debates sow division at one of Silicon Valley‚Äôs most powerful venture capital firms.

Sumaiya Balbale ‚Äî a practising Muslim who has spoken publicly about how her gender, ethnicity and faith have shaped her career ‚Äî stepped down after five years at the company in August. Her decision to leave was precipitated by Maguire‚Äôs social media posts, according to three people with knowledge of the matter.

Maguire, an outspoken and high-profile investor who is close to Elon Musk, wrote on X in July that New York mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani ‚Äúcomes from a culture that lies about everything. It‚Äôs literally a virtue to lie if it advances his Islamist agenda. The West will learn this lesson the hard way.‚Äù

Balbale complained to other senior partners at the firm, who declined to take action against Maguire, arguing he was just exercising his right to free speech, the people said. She left soon after, feeling her position was untenable.

Her departure caused consternation among staff and portfolio companies, the people said. Balbale, who is on the board of Shake Shack, was well regarded internally and by the start-ups she worked with as an experienced operating executive.

The meme of "my body is a machine that turns 'the passage of time' into 'not writing'." This is a joke about writing and how so much of writing is not writing‚Äî or at least, that's what I tell myself when I am avoiding writing, which is a big part of my actual job. I mean writing, not *not* writing. Bosses: do not look at this, especially if you are expecting something from me soon. Obviously, everything is going great. I am not procrastinating by making this meme. I am not deliberately wasting time in every possible way I can think of after already having made breakfast int he most laborious way possible, catching up on email and slack messages, engaging in some discord discourse, and checking every social media feed I have the misfortune to remain entangled with, and I fully intend on starting to write for real the moment I hit the button to send this tweet. Yes, I still call them tweets. It's an act of resistance at this point, calling them tweets. I remember there was some discussion of what to call them, and I have to say I did laugh about "skeets," since the act is comparable in some ways: it feels good in the moment, but results in something useless and gross just moments later... is this too much to get into here? I don't know if the wrongheadedly censorious people who run this platform even check descriptive alt text, come to think of it. Anyway, I should get back to writing, for real, which I will do now. That reminds me, did you catch the discourse the other day about dialogue choices in games? I don't have much to say, really, other than that creative works can be literally whatever you want them to be, so arguing about them isn't as productive as simply making the work you want to see in the world (and which I'll get back to doing in just a moment). If you want to see my approach to dialogue choices, why not play my visual novel, Eliza? If you've made it this far and haven't yet, I suggest you check it out. Okay, back to writing for real now. Definitely.

The Burgundian fusiliers are here to hold the line against the horrors of the Black Grail, a little preview of a 2026 KS in cooperation with Black Knight Miniatures ;3
#art #trenchcrusade
alt_text:
Four Burgundian soldiers, meant to be used as proxies for New Antioch Yeomen. They are wearing navy and red uniforms styled after French examples from the late 19th century, with polished brass fittings and chrome plated guns giving them a very ostentatious look befitting of the richest duchy in Europe. It consists in a short jacket with button up flaps below the hips, with red piping, epaulettes, insignias and facings, the later of which are sometimes X-shaped as a call back to the cross of Burgundy. The trousers are slightly baggy and tuck in halfway down the calves inside red spats.
The soldier on the left is a equipped for offense, with a Spencer shotgun and a large shield strapped with hand grenades on the inside. His uniforms is supplemented with white leather pteruges, a belt of full brass shot shells, a polished steel gorget and a matching burgonet with a a la romana crest.
The second soldier is equipped as a voltigeur with a short jacket and a tasseled forage cap. The standard issue rifle she's holding is a musket-like Lebel with a removable box magazine and decorative grooves in its stock, with a yatagan type bayonet.
The third soldier is equipped with a large harmonica carbine for which he is carrying several breech blocks in rows of pouches. He is wearing the standard issue shako of these troops fitted with braids, plumes and a polished brass crest. He is wearing a small target shield bearing the war flag of the dukes of burgundy on his left shoulder.
The fourth soldier is facing away to showcase the backpack, which is modeled after the standard French kit from the Belle Epoque.

caption:
I am studying for the American Planning Association's professional certification exam and I am kind of blown away by the planning profession's lack of faith in itself and confidence in its own judgment.

We know that building more lanes does not fix traffic congestion. We've known this for 75 years!
alt_text:
AICP Exam Prep: Sample Exam #2

You are the Director of Community and Economic Development for a large city. At a recent City Council meeting, you were directed to develop a response to a report issued by the regional MPO about trends in transportation in the region. Most of the report is focused on the impact cars are having on existing roads and the need for more freeways. The report indicates that the best way to reduce traffic congestion is to build more freeways and HOV lanes. You recognize that traffic is a hot button issue in your community, but you think the answer to traffic congestion is much more complicated than what is presented in the report. You have recently read reports that contradict the argument that building more roads solves traffic problems. In your report to the council, which of the following recommendations should you make?

Select one:

a. Recommend that key staff and councilmembers meet with the MPO to discuss the recommendations in the report and discuss how the MPO's findings could be incorporated into long-range transportation planning in the city.
b. Recommend that the report as submitted be adopted by the City Council, with the stipulation that you will meet with the MPO to express your concerns.
c. Ask the transportation division of your department to conduct a detailed transportation study and compare this to X the findings in the report.
d. Advise the City Council to reject the report since its recommendations are based on flawed reasoning.

MPOs and regional planning organizations are sometimes accused of prioritizing highway-building at the expense of transit, investment in transportation demand management, or other options. Your best course of action is to promote direct communication and try to emphasize the importance of integrating MPO objectives with the city's long range transportation planning objectives, which are likely to include transit and other alternatives.

The correct answer is: A

alt_text:
X (Twitter) Media Views & Media
View Rate
Media Views
Media Views simply refer to Video Views. By default, a "media view" occurs when at least 50% of the media is on the screen for at least
2-seconds. This means if a user scrolling through the X (Twitter) Feed sees at least half of the video frame on their screen for just 2-seconds, it will count as a "media view". Some would argue that this is not really a meaningful view which is why X (Twitter) also provide other video metrics such as views to 25%, 50%, 75% and 100% of the video length.
